From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Paul Philippov <paul@themactep.com>
Date: Sun, 28 Jun 2026 17:30:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] fix open64/fopen64/fseeko64 recursion

uClibc-ng's features.h unconditionally defines __USE_FILE_OFFSET64
on MIPS, which causes the C preprocessor to redirect:

  open    -> open64
  fopen   -> fopen64
  fseeko  -> fseeko64

This means open64() calling open() gets macro-expanded to
open64() calling open64() — infinite recursion, blowing the stack
with a SIGSEGV at the guard page.

Fix by #undef-ing each macro right before the function definition
that wraps it, so the function body calls the real libc symbol.

Signed-off-by: Paul Philippov <paul@themactep.com>

diff --git a/uclibc_shim.c b/uclibc_shim.c
index 7d15b5c..c893048 100644
--- a/uclibc_shim.c
+++ b/uclibc_shim.c
@@ -66,11 +66,13 @@ int __fputc_unlocked(int c, FILE *stream) {
 	return fputc(c, stream);
 }
 
+#undef fopen
 FILE* fopen64(const char *path, const char *mode) {
 	DEBUG_PRINT(stderr, "[WARNING] Called fopen64. This is a shim and does nothing.\n");
 	return fopen(path, mode);
 }
 
+#undef open
 int open64(const char *path, int flags, ...) {
 	mode_t mode = 0;
 
@@ -90,6 +92,7 @@ int open64(const char *path, int flags, ...) {
 	}
 }
 
+#undef fseeko
 int fseeko64(FILE *stream, off_t offset, int whence) {
 	DEBUG_PRINT(stderr, "[WARNING] Called fseeko64. This is a shim and does nothing.\n");
 	return fseeko(stream, offset, whence);
